body:
@rhauch Thanks for the comments here, they are quite helpful in understanding the motivations. 

I think of "users" of Kafka Streams mainly in two categories: 1) application developers who are only interested in the computational logics, who would not be interested in learning Kafka specs like partition assignment and task migration, state management / serdes, stream-time extraction, etc; for example, "as a data scientist I should not need to worry which partition this record is going to while coding my stream analytics application". 2) framework developers, who can then extend the interfaces like StateStore, TimestampExtractor, PartitionGrouper, Partitioner, Seriailizer etc. When I talked about "confusing users" I meant this KStreamPartitioner will be exposed to the first categories of users who would then be forced to learn how to specify the partitioning for Kafka, what are the other uses of this topic in the Kafka cluster, etc, while it would be great if we could expose it only to the second group of users, who would then design those functions and wrap them as config values for the first group of users to apply. And by reducing the control of partitioners only to a small group of users the likelihood of conflicting partitioning schemes for shared topics would also be reduced (as I meant for "less vulnerable").

That said, if moving forward we realize there is no clear boundary between these two groups of users and people treat it as less burden to be exposed to some low-level details in their APIs we can consider adding them back. Thoughts?

@gwenshap I think installing real Kerberos in the VM seems the best play overall. It would give us a better level of confidence around the whole deployment. I don't have a clear sense for how complicated that is or if it would affect our flexibility in any way. I haven't used Kerberos before. I know @harshach has a VM with Kerberos in, although it didn't work for me on first execution. Maybe you could comment on the complexity here @harshach?

I'm not sure forking MiniKDC buys us all that much, but it may be worth merging this as a temporary measure so that people can at least run Kerberos based tests locally. 

Let me know what you want to do.
